00:08.880 --> 00:12.780
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.440 --> 00:33.780
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:36.420 --> 00:38.120
And here are your hosts.

00:42.040 --> 00:49.880
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Ray Bradbury has tried just about every
form of writing an author can undertake. Short stories, novels, poetry, plays,

00:50.100 --> 00:57.480
even an opera. And he's also written numerous television and movie scripts. He
used to write shows back in the 60s for Twilight Zone and Alfred Hitchcock. I

00:57.480 --> 01:10.040
did three one-hour shows for Hitchcock for his big one-hour series. And then I
did eight or nine scripts, maybe ten or twelve, for the half-hour series. And

01:10.040 --> 01:17.600
all but one of those were my own stories. We asked Bradbury if he still does
television scripts, particularly the kind that are written on cue with the

01:17.600 --> 01:30.200
deadline. Well, I tried never to do that anyway. I had a very friendly
relationship with Alfred Hitchcock and all of his partners there, Joan Harrison

01:30.200 --> 01:40.720
and Norman Lloyd. I'd go out and have a casual lunch, tell them an idea. They'd
okay it. I'd go home and write it and come back with a finished script. And we'd

01:40.720 --> 01:49.640
have another lunch. And if they could argue me into any changes, I'd make them.
And if I could argue them into the logic of my situation, it stayed the way it

01:49.640 --> 02:00.820
was. So it was a very amiable, very friendly thing. I never did a lot of
scripts. I wouldn't let myself get bullied into being a full-time writer because

02:00.820 --> 02:09.760
no one remembers who writes scripts for television anyway. Bradbury still writes
for television occasionally. Last year he had two shows that were successful,

02:10.000 --> 02:17.140
The Electric Grandmother and Any Friend of Nicholas Nickleby is a Friend of
Mine. That last work is based on a play Bradbury had written. We asked him how

02:17.140 --> 02:29.720
many of his plays have been produced. Oh, I would say somewhere around 14 or 15
of them. Most of them I've produced myself. Dandelion Wine here on the coast

02:29.720 --> 02:41.120
recently, back east a few years ago. The Martian Chronicles, which I produced
here at a small theater. Fahrenheit 451, two years ago, which turned out very

02:41.120 --> 02:54.700
well. The Wonderful Ice Cream Suit, then six or seven of my one-act plays. I've
had The Anthem Sprinters, which is all of my Irish experiences. So I've had a

02:54.700 --> 03:03.280
lot of fun with it, and I've made a lot of friends among actors. I've worked
with a lot of good people, including James Whitmore, who appeared in my first

03:03.280 --> 03:13.020
one-act play here. And it'll benefit for the United Nations about 23 years ago.
It's obvious from all of Bradbury's fiction that he is a lover of books.

03:13.160 --> 03:22.440
Fahrenheit 451 is a good example of that. We wondered, then, how he could devote
so much energy to the visual arts like television or the movies. I grew up with

03:22.440 --> 03:32.100
all these loves. If I have any capacity at all, it's to be in love in six or
seven different ways. So I've always been madly in love with motion pictures. My

03:32.100 --> 03:46.180
mother was a fiend for them and took me to see hundreds of films from the age of
when I was two up until I was 10, 11, or 12. So that never left me. And I think

03:46.180 --> 03:57.760
I'm very fortunate to have a great love of films, a great love of libraries and
books, a great love of radio and the famous people in radio. When I came west to

03:57.760 --> 04:07.980
live in Los Angeles, I headed downtown immediately and got to know all the
people on an old radio broadcast called Hollywood Hotel. And Louella Parsons

04:07.980 --> 04:23.380
became a friend to this 13-, 14-year-old boy. And I knew Burns and Allen during
those years of 1934, 35, 36. I wrote scripts for them every week and handed them

04:23.380 --> 04:35.080
in. Of course, I doubt if they even read them, but they pretended that they did.
And they were very kind to me. And then I was in love with Orson Welles when he

04:35.080 --> 04:46.720
came on the scene in radio and suspense. And Norman Corwin, who became my friend
when I was 27 years old. So I grew up then with a love of libraries, a love of

04:46.720 --> 04:58.580
radio, a love of films. And I think I'm very lucky that I've been able to work
in all of these different mediums and do rather well in each one of them. More

04:58.580 --> 04:59.660
next time with Ray Bradbury.

05:07.020 --> 05:14.840
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

05:14.840 --> 05:18.480
Odessa, Texas. 

06:04.360 --> 06:08.300
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:24.140 --> 06:29.380
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:32.140 --> 06:33.700
And here are your hosts.

06:37.700 --> 06:45.720
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Ray Bradbury, who most readers recognize as
a science fiction author, has been writing poetry for most of his life. And he

06:45.720 --> 06:52.520
publishes it regularly, too, in all sorts of magazines. Every so often the poems
are collected together in a single volume. There have been four of these

06:52.520 --> 07:00.680
collections so far. When Elephants Last in the Door Yard Bloomed, Where Robot
Mice and Robot Men Run Round in Robot Towns, The Haunted Computer and the

07:00.680 --> 07:08.380
Android Pope, and most recently, The Complete Poems of Ray Bradbury. Not all of
Bradbury's verse is science fiction or fantasy, but a bunch of it is. One of our

07:08.380 --> 07:16.120
favorites, for instance, is called The Haunted Computer and the Android Pope.
Sometimes his poetry has a bite to it or a message. Abandoned in Place is one of

07:16.120 --> 07:23.280
these. It's a lament for the neglected American space program. We ask Bradbury,
when he sits down to write, what determines what will come out? A story? A

07:23.280 --> 07:34.160
novel? A play? An opera? Whatever. I haven't the faintest idea. It just knocks
me over. Sometimes in the middle of writing a poem, I'll say, oh my, this is too

07:34.160 --> 07:44.960
big for a poem. I may very well finish the poem, but then I sit down and turn it
into a short story immediately. Or on a rare occasion, it turns into a stage

07:44.960 --> 07:58.500
play or a novel. But that doesn't happen as often. Most of the time, I work in
the short form. But quite often, you take the simplest idea and it evolves from

07:58.500 --> 08:11.520
the poetry form into, well, I was, for instance, I was driving around in England
a few years ago and a chauffeur of our car was talking about driving and the

08:11.520 --> 08:23.580
Irish and funerals, the Irish wakes and what have you. And he told of this one
wake of some friends of his in a small town in Ireland where an English lord

08:23.580 --> 08:34.920
lived nearby. And when he died, he went against the old saying, you can't take
it with you. And he took with him all of his wine and he had all the thousands

08:34.920 --> 08:46.940
of bottles of wine in his cellar poured into his grave. Well, it was such a
great idea that I wrote it as a short story last week and sent it off and it'll

08:46.940 --> 08:56.520
probably be in Playboy sometime in the next two or four, five months. We asked
Bradbury if he could name one or two of his favorite poems from his own work. At

08:56.520 --> 09:04.660
the time I write them, of course, I think each one is good or I wouldn't have
put it in the book. I try not to ever publish a poem or a short story that I've

09:04.660 --> 09:13.300
gotten tired of. With his incredibly busy schedule, will he continue to write
poetry? Oh, yes, yes, yes.

09:21.780 --> 09:27.740
Those science fiction fans who might have been surprised that Bradbury writes
poetry, we have another surprise ahead of them. When we asked Bradbury if there

09:27.740 --> 09:37.620
was a form of writing he hadn't tried yet, his answer contained a mild shocker.
I can't think of anything offhand. Now that I'm working on this libretto for

09:37.620 --> 09:48.820
this opera, that sort of rounds out the list. I'm working on a detective murder
mystery novel now, which I've never done before. So it's a new, it's a change

09:48.820 --> 10:00.020
for me in the novel form. I've been a great lover and admirer of Dashiell
Hammett and Raymond Chandler for the last 40 years or so. And I always wanted to

10:00.020 --> 10:09.400
do something in that field. But I was afraid to do it because I wasn't well
enough educated, even though I'd read hundreds of novels in the field when I was

10:09.400 --> 10:18.700
younger. It didn't seem to get into my bloodstream. But now I think I'm old
enough and I hope I've learned my lessons. And when the novel comes out, people

10:18.700 --> 10:28.580
will agree that it's at least an agreeable competitor in the field. Could he
tell us when the novel might be published? No, I would say about a year from

10:28.580 --> 10:38.260
now. It's right up close to being finished. I've been working on it seven or
eight years. But you never know. I might finish it all in one week in the next

10:38.260 --> 10:48.840
week or two. And again, I may drag on for another six months. I'm not in charge.
I don't make the decisions. We'll have more next time with Ray Bradbury.

10:56.120 --> 11:03.600
