11:55.220 --> 11:59.120
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:14.920 --> 12:20.180
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

12:22.920 --> 12:24.540
And here are your hosts.

12:28.560 --> 12:36.540
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Ray Bradbury has always been impossible to
categorize. He writes science fiction and fantasy, and much of his reputation is

12:36.540 --> 12:44.140
based on books like The Martian Chronicles and Fahrenheit 451. But he's also
written mainstream material like Dandelion Wine. He's also been successful with

12:44.140 --> 12:51.780
poetry, drama, movie scripts, and is now working on a grand opera. We asked
Bradbury if it ever bothers him to be labeled as a science fiction writer. Well,

12:52.040 --> 13:00.960
it depends on how it's used. Some people use it with prejudice. There are still
some librarians in the country. There are still some critics. There are still

13:00.960 --> 13:12.960
some teachers who think that science fiction isn't worth bothering with. And of
course, that drives me wild. So their opinion actually irritates me because, to

13:12.960 --> 13:21.720
me, it's the central fiction of our time. We are a science-oriented,
technologically-oriented people. And there's nothing else to write about except

13:21.720 --> 13:32.760
human beings in some sort of relationship with their ideas, with their
machineries, with their technologies. All the major problems of our time right

13:32.760 --> 13:43.520
now are technological, scientific, moral problems. What do you do with the
automobile? What do you do with nuclear power? What do you do with cloning? What

13:43.520 --> 13:56.380
do you do with DNA experimentation? All these problems that arise as soon as you
invent something new. So all of our major problems right now, you can't name one

13:56.380 --> 14:05.420
that's not connected to a machine somewhere down the line. What about those hard
-headed, practical sort of people who have no use for imaginative literature and

14:05.420 --> 14:15.960
call it useless? Well, there's always been bad talk among intellectuals who
don't stop and think what they're saying. It's a very dumb remark. I mean, if

14:15.960 --> 14:26.560
you don't have an imagination, you can't survive. If you don't have some sort of
creative instinct in you, how do you think people survive Buchenwald? Those who

14:26.560 --> 14:36.980
survive, survive with their imagination. A lot of them were able to imagine. At
times, for a little while, they were somewhere else. If you're in a jail and

14:36.980 --> 14:46.540
people are dying all around you, you damn well better have the power of
imagination so that you can imagine a future where this will stop or you can

14:46.540 --> 14:56.540
imagine a present where you're not there for a little while. To live inside your
head and to forget the horror that surrounds you. That's a huge thing to be able

14:56.540 --> 15:09.300
to do. A lot of people did it. It's remarkable. It's miraculous. But that's what
a human being is. A miraculous animal in the history of the world who's able to

15:09.300 --> 15:09.740
survive.

15:15.940 --> 15:25.440
We asked Bradbury what part of his work he'd like to be remembered for one or
two hundred years from now. Oh, I hope that something wicked this way comes is

15:25.440 --> 15:37.460
still around. I think it's a universal book. At least I hope it is. It deals
with children and growing up and growing old and getting sick and dying. All the

15:37.460 --> 15:47.800
things that happened to all the people in the history of the world. Well, I hope
the book won't age, that it would belong to no special time, but to all times.

15:48.120 --> 15:57.740
It's my favorite, and I love it because I suppose I'm locked into it with my
father. My father is the hero of the book, and I didn't know that at the time I

15:57.740 --> 16:07.360
wrote it. One night I got up and wandered around the house and picked up the
book and started to reread it and suddenly cried out and tears burst from my

16:07.360 --> 16:19.560
eyes, and I realized that I'd written my father into the book as Mr. Holloway,
who is the hero of the entire structure of the book. So that's one of the

16:19.560 --> 16:29.760
reasons why I love it, and I hope it'll have a little life after I'm gone.
Something Wicked This Way Comes is indeed a classic in the fantasy horror genre.

16:30.020 --> 16:36.440
And it will be out as a major Hollywood motion picture soon. It's being done by
Walt Disney, and Bradbury wrote the script for the screen version. It should be

16:36.440 --> 16:39.980
a great one. We'll conclude our conversation with Ray Bradbury on our next show.

16:47.220 --> 16:55.000
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in

16:55.000 --> 16:55.760
Odessa, Texas.

