18:14.040 --> 18:15.740
And here are your hosts.

18:19.880 --> 18:26.500
This is Daryl Lane and David Carson. Anyone familiar with the stories of Ray
Bradbury will know that he occasionally writes something in praise of George

18:26.500 --> 18:37.140
Bernard Shaw. We asked him why he thought so much of Shaw. My God, he is, of all
the writers of our time, just about, at least on the, when you think of Irish

18:37.140 --> 18:49.920
-English literature for the theater, he is the idea writer of all idea writers.
He and G.K. Chesterton, and a few others, but he sort of outraces and outpaces

18:49.920 --> 18:59.600
everyone. You name a subject, and he just pretty well wrote about it 70 years
ago, 100 years ago, 90 years ago. He was interested in theology. He was

18:59.600 --> 19:12.300
interested in machinery. He was interested in the future. He was interested in
biology. He had a far-ranging curiosity about mankind and the future of mankind.

19:12.780 --> 19:23.040
So he wrote science fiction, as well as doing theological studies and great
characters from history like St. John.

19:31.860 --> 19:42.280
What kinds of books would Bradbury choose to educate children today? Oh, I would
recommend George Bernard Shaw as soon as someone was old enough. I don't think

19:42.280 --> 19:54.580
you can give Shaw to children, nor can you give him to kids in high school. But
as soon as people get into college, then I would bring Shaw out and give them a

19:54.580 --> 20:06.560
complete education in ideas and how to think. And at the lower level, I imagine
I would start them out with Jules Verne and H.G. Wells, the science fiction

20:06.560 --> 20:22.180
writers, because kids really are interested in ideas. And it's very playful.
It's wonderful to have an interest in such things. And that's the reason why

20:22.180 --> 20:32.020
science fiction during the last few years has been so popular in the high
schools and the junior high schools. The kids recognize that these fictions deal

20:32.020 --> 20:38.840
with very real problems that must be solved. And you have the fun of playing
with those toys inside your head.

20:47.000 --> 20:53.600
Of course, Bradbury is still going full speed writing his own fiction of all
sorts. When we asked him what he was working on at the present time, he

20:53.600 --> 21:01.180
mentioned the usual things, such as poetry, short stories, a novel, even
something unusual, a grand opera. But he's also shaping up something else that

21:01.180 --> 21:13.940
should be fascinating to all readers. I've written a sort of autobiographical
charting of where I get my ideas and how I wrote all of my novels. I want to do

21:13.940 --> 21:27.700
a sort of book similar to, but certainly not equal to, The Summing Up by
Somerset Maugham. And I think ideas are fascinating. Where do you get a story

21:27.700 --> 21:37.980
idea and what do you do with it? And after all, I've written 400 or 500 stories.
So that would make, I think, an interesting book and not a boring one. I don't

21:37.980 --> 21:49.900
like to read autobiographies where they take a thousand pages to go through
their childhood. I'm really not interested in the facts of people's lives. It's

21:49.900 --> 22:00.420
a rare person who can write about their childhood or their sexuality and be
interesting and amusing. I don't care what kind of sex life anyone has had. I

22:00.420 --> 22:10.100
don't want to know a thing about George Bernard Shaw or Somerset Maugham or
Shakespeare and these others. I have no interest in their sex life. I have only

22:10.100 --> 22:20.660
a huge and pervading interest in their ideas, where they got them and what they
did with them. So that's the kind of book I'm doing. You won't find any gossip

22:20.660 --> 22:31.700
in it. You won't find out anything horrendous about me or anyone else. It's just
how I stumble over things, pick myself up, dust myself off, and write a poem.

22:39.220 --> 22:47.100
