24:01.720 --> 24:03.160
And here are your hosts.

24:07.420 --> 24:14.500
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Jessica Amanda Salmonson has been a
professional writer and editor of fantasy for only a few years, but she's made

24:14.500 --> 24:22.660
her influence felt. In 1980, her first professional work, Amazons!, an anthology
she edited for DAW Books, won an award as the Best Fantasy Anthology of the

24:22.660 --> 24:30.680
Year. And she's written three novels of heroic fantasy. Two of them involve a
woman samurai warrior named Tomoe Gozen. The first one, entitled Tomoe Gozen,

24:30.680 --> 24:40.260
was published in 1981. The second, called The Golden Naginata, came out in 1982.
She also edited another fantasy anthology in 1982 called Amazons II, and

24:40.260 --> 24:46.880
she'll have much more work coming out in the future. We spoke with Salmonson
recently about her involvement in the field of fantasy. We wondered if she grew

24:46.880 --> 24:56.860
up reading science fiction pulp magazines, as many contemporary authors have. I
never liked the pulps particularly. I liked fairy tales when I was quite little,

24:56.880 --> 25:08.060
but somehow I never thought of them as being suitable for me as a teenage reader
or as an adult reader. It took me a long time to connect and see that fantasy

25:08.060 --> 25:18.300
was really suited for adults as well. I think a lot of people feel that way
about fantasy. They start reading science fiction perhaps partly because it

25:18.300 --> 25:31.380
seems more adult than fantasy. I don't think that's at all true. Fantasy has
stronger symbolic meaning, whereas science fiction in a lot of ways is a lot

25:31.380 --> 25:44.160
more simplistic. It's world views, feeling around for symbols that don't have an
ancient heritage or an ancient long existence in our subconscious and our

25:44.160 --> 25:54.620
culture. We ask her why fantasy, particularly heroic fantasy, is so popular
these days. Why do people read it? I don't think you can generalize why people

25:54.620 --> 26:11.420
like it. I think for some people it has very deep symbolic meaning in their
personal daily lives. Obviously nobody is really a big tough swords master who

26:11.420 --> 26:24.060
can win their way through any problem. But I think that there is a relationship
between these fantasies and the real world that's not just escapist in that our

26:24.060 --> 26:35.140
daily lives are pretty dangerous and we somehow manage to survive and go to the
end of our lives anyway. So there is a, it's kind of, I suppose, burlesque and

26:35.140 --> 26:45.980
extreme. But the heroic fantasy world is very much like our own world and the
dangers we manage to survive day after day. Also the amount of death and the

26:45.980 --> 26:55.780
blood and gore that exists in these kinds of novels is to many people
exploitative and grotesque. It's just they don't like it. They don't know why so

26:55.780 --> 27:07.880
many other people do like it. And they think very badly of that form of
literature because it is so bloody. But to me, I think there is definitely that

27:07.880 --> 27:17.460
exploit to that aspect of it. But I think it's also, again, symbolic of, say,
the transience of our own life. At any moment you could get smashed to

27:17.460 --> 27:28.820
smithereens in a car crash. Life can just end suddenly. And even if you live a
long life, 80 years or 60 years, it's just not a long time. And the sudden death

27:28.820 --> 27:40.880
and the danger that these worlds represent is very much like our own world.
They're very honest in a way. Finally, we inquired about the relation of fantasy

27:40.880 --> 27:56.760
and fairy tales. In most cases, I think one is the direct outgrowth of the
other. But heroic fantasy probably has its most obvious roots in ancient epics

27:56.760 --> 28:12.520
from Gilgamesh or Jason and the Argonauts. Anything like that is probably its
most obvious roots. But in the nature of storytelling in prose form, it's more

28:12.520 --> 28:13.880
related to the fairy tales.

28:21.020 --> 28:28.900
